    {
      "text": "A 1.5-month-old male infant presents to the outpatient department with vomiting after feeding and failure to thrive. On examination, a firm, olive-shaped mass is palpated in the upper abdomen. What is the most likely diagnosis?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Subacute Intestinal Obstruction"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Pyloric Stenosis"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "GERD"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Esophageal Atresia"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Answer: B) <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1f1a14b77a16927771969d5c9e8bd2\">Pyloric Stenosis</span> </strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><strong>Projectile, non-bilious vomiting</strong> is the hallmark of <strong>infantile <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"2cf4f27ae616927771895f410747ad\">hypertrophic pyloric stenosis</span> (IHPS)</strong>.</li>\n\t<li>The presence of a <strong>firm, olive-shaped mass</strong> in the <strong>epigastric region</strong> (hypertrophied pylorus) is a classic finding.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Failure to thrive</strong> occurs due to <strong>chronic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"998fb41ebc1692777202e46891c4a7\">vomiting</span> and dehydration</strong>.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Ultrasound confirms the diagnosis</strong> by showing <strong>thickened pyloric muscle (>3mm thickness, >14mm length)</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3><strong>Hypertrophic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1f1a14b77a16927771969d5c9e8bd2\">Pyloric Stenosis</span> (HPS)</strong></h3>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:421px\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Feature</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Description</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Age of Presentation</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>3-6 weeks of life</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Symptoms</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>Projectile, non-bilious vomiting</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Physical Exam</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>Olive-shaped mass in epigastrium</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Diagnosis</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>Ultrasound: Pyloric muscle hypertrophy</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Treatment</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Ramstedt's pyloromyotomy</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"\" data-source=\"\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"448\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/UIu3Uu2ja3gXkt5yywRZ1741075174.png\" width=\"444\" /></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Subacute <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fb7b40ddbe1692777190ca311f4bd7\">Intestinal Obstruction</span> (Option A):</strong> <strong>Incorrect</strong> because it typically presents with <strong>bilious vomiting</strong> and <strong>distended abdomen</strong>, not an <strong>olive-shaped mass</strong>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>GERD (Option C):</strong> <strong>Incorrect</strong> because <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"01e03927231692777188168edc7b35\">GERD</span> causes <strong>effortless regurgitation</strong> without an <strong>olive-shaped mass</strong> or projectile vomiting.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Esophageal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5c10d19e4416927771829871a1737f\">Atresia</span> (Option D):</strong> <strong>Incorrect</strong> because it presents <strong>at birth</strong> with <strong>excessive drooling, choking, and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cfad80a0f716927771979aae100f95\">respiratory</span> distress</strong>, not progressive vomiting.</p>\n\n<p> </p>",
