    {
      "text": "Which of the following gene mutations are involved in carcinoma of the colon?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "APC, BRCA, k-ras"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "APC, k-ras, p53"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "MYh, K-RAS, APC"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "MYH, p53, DCC"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: B) APC, k-ras, p53</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>The genes associated with the development of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f04bf2125316927771847bfe139191\">colorectal</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"988c19e3131692777183b6744d1920\">carcinoma</span> are <strong>APC, k-ras, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"14caf753cb169277719405bdd25002\">p53</span> & </strong>SMAD4.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Adenoma-Carcinoma Sequence:</strong> Accounts for up to 80% of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a325d0c14e16927771992fe8a96758\">sporadic</span> cancers.</li>\n\t<li>APC Gene Mutations:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Leads to β-catenin accumulation and Wnt <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3aa5abc2fa169277719488e088076d\">pathway</span> activation.</li>\n\t\t<li>\"First hit\": <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a325d0c14e16927771992fe8a96758\">Sporadic</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"2f7bf58a321692777190e32a914615\">inactivation</span> of APC.</li>\n\t\t<li>\"Second hit\": Loss of second <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f2ee7650b0169277718135012a6c14\">APC</span> copy</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>K-ras Mutations:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Promote growth and prevent apoptosis.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>SMAD2 and SMAD4 Mutations:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Disrupt TGF-β pathway, causing uncontrolled proliferation.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>p53 Mutations:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Occur in later stages of tumour progression.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"\" data-source=\"\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"459\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/v2LXCinJ9IHT6vRt5dOK1745476398.png\" width=\"500\" /></p>\n\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"> </h3>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img alt=\"Fearon and Vogelstein's model for the development of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f04bf2125316927771847bfe139191\">colorectal</span> cancer\" data-author=\"\" data-hash=\"12179\" data-license=\"\" data-source=\"\" data-tags=\"May2025\" height=\"210\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/0wEnjsz1KsbQFf4gR7Mn1746521428.png\" width=\"500\" /></p>\n\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Fearon and Vogelstein's model for the development of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f04bf2125316927771847bfe139191\">colorectal</span> cancer </strong></h3>\n\n<p><strong>APC, BRCA, k-ras (Option A):</strong> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4ac7eaee731692777183d4cf007d30\">BRCA</span> mutations are more commonly associated with breast and ovarian cancers, not <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0fce15e71f1692777184feb9af5303\">colon</span> cancer.</p>\n\n<p><strong>MYh, K-RAS, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f2ee7650b0169277718135012a6c14\">APC</span> (Option C):</strong> <strong>MYH-associated <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fe6b8df2fa1692777196938c42762a\">polyposis</span> (MAP)</strong> is a rare autosomal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d54db2110416927771971e7c011a9f\">recessive</span> condition caused by mutations in the <strong>MUTYH</strong> gene. It can increase the risk of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f04bf2125316927771847bfe139191\">colorectal</span> cancer, but <strong>MUTYH</strong> gene mutations are not directly associated with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0fce15e71f1692777184feb9af5303\">colon</span> cancer.</p>\n\n<p><strong>MYH, p53, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f126e2c1731692777185ce4a46bae3\">DCC</span> (Option D): </strong> <strong>MYH-associated <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fe6b8df2fa1692777196938c42762a\">polyposis</span> (MAP)</strong> is a rare autosomal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d54db2110416927771971e7c011a9f\">recessive</span> condition caused by mutations in the <strong>MUTYH</strong> gene. It can increase the risk of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f04bf2125316927771847bfe139191\">colorectal</span> cancer, but <strong>MUTYH</strong> gene mutations are not directly associated with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0fce15e71f1692777184feb9af5303\">colon</span> cancer.</p>",
